---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import '../../styles/global.css';
import '../../styles/course.css';
import LessonPage from '../../components/course/LessonPage';
import GatePanel from '../../components/assessment/GatePanel';
---

<BaseLayout title="A Speedup Is Not Valid Until You Validate Outputs">
  <LessonPage lessonId="L38" client:load>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Question</div>
      <div class="lesson-question">How do you know a speedup is safe?</div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Intuition</div>
      <p>
        Making inference faster is only useful if the model still produces correct outputs. Many optimizations &mdash; quantization, kernel rewrites, layout changes, reduced precision &mdash; can subtly alter the numbers flowing through the model. A speed benchmark alone (tokens per second) cannot detect whether the outputs have degraded.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Logits comparison</strong> is the most direct check: run the same prompt through the original and optimized models and compare the raw logit vectors. For lossless changes (repack, thread count), the logits should match within floating-point epsilon. For lossy changes (quantization, reduced precision), the logits <em>will</em> differ — the question is whether the difference is acceptable. Logit comparison alone cannot answer that; you need perplexity or task-level evaluation.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Perplexity</strong> provides a higher-level check. Perplexity measures how surprised the model is by a test dataset &mdash; specifically, it is the exponentiated average negative log-likelihood of the correct next token. <em>Lower</em> perplexity means the model assigns higher probability to the right answers, which means better predictions. Typical large models score around 5&ndash;8 on wikitext-2. If your model scores 7.2 before an optimization and 7.3 after, that is likely within tolerance. If it jumps to 9.0+, something has broken. If perplexity increases meaningfully after an optimization, the model has gotten worse at predicting, even if it runs faster.
      </p>
      <p>
        A valid speedup shows: same or negligibly different logits, and no perplexity regression on a standard test set.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">How to Compare Logits</div>
      <p>
        "Compare the logits" sounds simple, but there are several ways to measure divergence, each catching different
        kinds of problems:
      </p>
      <div style="margin: var(--space-4) 0;">
        <p style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--ink-primary);">1. Max absolute difference</p>
        <p>
          For each token position, compute max|logit_baseline - logit_optimized| across the vocabulary. This catches
          the worst-case divergence. For lossless optimizations (repack, thread count changes), this should be zero
          or within floating-point epsilon (~1e-5 for FP32, ~1e-3 for FP16). If the max diff exceeds 0.01, something
          has changed beyond rounding.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div style="margin: var(--space-4) 0;">
        <p style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--ink-primary);">2. Cosine similarity of logit vectors</p>
        <p>
          Treat each position's logit vector as a point in vocab_size-dimensional space. Cosine similarity near 1.0
          means the <em>ranking</em> of tokens is preserved even if absolute values shifted. This is useful for lossy
          optimizations like quantization: the absolute logits will differ, but if the model still ranks the same
          tokens highest, behavior is likely preserved. A cosine similarity below 0.999 at any position warrants
          investigation.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div style="margin: var(--space-4) 0;">
        <p style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--ink-primary);">3. KL divergence of probability distributions</p>
        <p>
          Convert logits to probabilities (softmax), then compute KL(baseline || optimized). This measures how much
          the <em>sampling distribution</em> has changed. KL divergence is sensitive to changes in the tail of the
          distribution — tokens with low probability. A KL divergence above 0.01 nats averaged across positions
          suggests meaningful behavioral change.
        </p>
      </div>
      <p>
        In practice, start with max absolute difference for lossless changes and perplexity for lossy ones. Use cosine
        similarity and KL divergence when you need to understand <em>how</em> the outputs differ, not just <em>whether</em>
        they differ.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">The Practical Validation Workflow</div>
      <p>
        A disciplined validation process follows a specific order, because each step catches different failure modes:
      </p>
      <ol style="list-style: decimal; padding-left: var(--space-5); margin: var(--space-3) 0;">
        <li style="padding: var(--space-1) 0; font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          <strong>Bitwise logit comparison on a short prompt.</strong> Run 5-10 prompts through both baseline and optimized.
          Compare raw logits. If max absolute diff is zero (or within FP epsilon), you have strong evidence that
          the optimization is numerically identical for the tested inputs. (Edge-case shapes may still differ — see step 4.)
        </li>
        <li style="padding: var(--space-1) 0; font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          <strong>Perplexity on a reference dataset.</strong> If logits differ (expected for quantization, precision
          changes), measure perplexity on wikitext-2 or a similar standard set. Compare against the baseline number.
          Record both numbers and the delta.
        </li>
        <li style="padding: var(--space-1) 0; font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          <strong>Generation quality spot-check.</strong> Run the model on a diverse set of prompts (code, reasoning,
          factual recall, creative) and manually inspect the outputs. Perplexity can miss mode collapse or systematic
          biases that only appear for certain prompt types.
        </li>
        <li style="padding: var(--space-1) 0; font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          <strong>Edge-case testing.</strong> Try inputs that stress the optimization: very long contexts, unusual
          token sequences, inputs that trigger all branches of a fused kernel. Many bugs only manifest for specific
          input shapes (e.g., dimensions not divisible by the SIMD width).
        </li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        Steps 1-2 should be automated and run in CI. Steps 3-4 are manual but essential for high-risk changes.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Common Failure Modes</div>
      <p>
        Understanding how optimizations typically fail helps you know what to look for:
      </p>
      <ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: var(--space-3) 0;">
        <li style="padding: var(--space-2) 0; font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          <strong>Stride/alignment bugs in repack:</strong> The weights are rearranged in memory but a stride
          calculation is off by one element. Most layers work fine (dimensions happen to be aligned), but a few
          layers silently read wrong values. Perplexity increases slightly — easy to miss without automated checks.
        </li>
        <li style="padding: var(--space-2) 0; font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          <strong>Precision loss in fused kernels:</strong> A fused kernel combines multiple operations (e.g., GEMV +
          bias + activation) using intermediate FP16 where the original used FP32. Each step loses a small amount of
          precision. Individually negligible, but compounded across 32+ layers the error grows.
        </li>
        <li style="padding: var(--space-2) 0; font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          <strong>Quantization of sensitive layers:</strong> Not all layers tolerate quantization equally. Attention
          projection layers (especially Q and K) are often more sensitive than FFN layers. A uniform quantization scheme
          that works on average may degrade specific layers badly.
        </li>
        <li style="padding: var(--space-2) 0; font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          <strong>Non-determinism from threading:</strong> Changing the thread count or thread dispatch order can change
          the order of floating-point additions. Due to non-associativity of FP math (a+b)+c &ne; a+(b+c), this
          produces different results. Usually within tolerance, but it means logit comparison must account for FP
          non-determinism.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Toy Example</div>
      <div class="toy-example">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">
          Comparing baseline vs optimized on a test set:
        </p>
        <div style="font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm);">
          <div style="margin-bottom: var(--space-3); padding: var(--space-3); background: var(--surface-3); border-radius: var(--radius-sm);">
            <div style="color: var(--sem-ffn); font-weight: 600;">Optimization A (safe repack):</div>
            <div style="padding-left: var(--space-4); margin-top: var(--space-1);">
              <div>Speed: 42 tok/s &rarr; 51 tok/s &nbsp;<span style="color: var(--sem-ffn);">(+21%)</span></div>
              <div>Max logit diff: 0.00001 &nbsp;<span style="color: var(--ink-tertiary);">(FP rounding only)</span></div>
              <div>Perplexity: 5.82 &rarr; 5.82 &nbsp;<span style="color: var(--sem-ffn);">(unchanged)</span></div>
              <div style="color: var(--sem-ffn); margin-top: var(--space-1);">Valid speedup.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div style="padding: var(--space-3); background: var(--surface-3); border-radius: var(--radius-sm);">
            <div style="color: var(--sem-attention); font-weight: 600;">Optimization B (aggressive quantization):</div>
            <div style="padding-left: var(--space-4); margin-top: var(--space-1);">
              <div>Speed: 42 tok/s &rarr; 68 tok/s &nbsp;<span style="color: var(--sem-ffn);">(+62%)</span></div>
              <div>Max logit diff: 2.4 &nbsp;<span style="color: var(--sem-attention);">(significant divergence)</span></div>
              <div>Perplexity: 5.82 &rarr; 6.41 &nbsp;<span style="color: var(--sem-attention);">(+10% regression)</span></div>
              <div style="color: var(--sem-attention); margin-top: var(--space-1);">Faster but different logits &mdash; not a valid drop-in replacement.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Shapes</div>
      <div class="shape-card">
        <div>Logits vector: [vocab_size] per token position</div>
        <div>Perplexity: scalar computed over a test set of N tokens</div>
        <div style="color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-top: var(--space-2);">
          Logit comparison is per-token and per-position. Perplexity is a single aggregate number summarizing prediction quality across the entire test set.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Math</div>
      <div style="font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm); background: var(--surface-3); padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4); border-radius: var(--radius-sm); margin: var(--space-3) 0;">
        <div style="color: var(--sem-token);">perplexity = exp( &minus;(1/N) &sum;&#x1D62; log P(token&#x1D62; | context&#x1D62;) )</div>
        <div style="color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-top: var(--space-2);">
          P(token&#x1D62; | context&#x1D62;) is the model's predicted probability for the correct next token at position i.
        </div>
        <div style="color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-top: var(--space-2);">
          Lower perplexity = higher average probability assigned to correct tokens = better model.
        </div>
        <div style="color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-top: var(--space-2);">
          A perplexity of 1.0 means the model perfectly predicts every token. Real models on wikitext-2 typically score 5&ndash;10.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Implementation Hook</div>
      <div class="impl-hook">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          In <code>llama.cpp</code>, the <code>perplexity</code> tool evaluates a model on a test dataset (typically wikitext-2) and reports perplexity. This is the standard way to check whether a quantization or kernel change has regressed model quality. Running it before and after any optimization is essential practice.
        </p>
        <div class="file-path"><a href="https://github.com/ggml-org/llama.cpp/blob/94ca829b6001019622c0f67fcd48e9ec6bd7dce8/tools/perplexity/perplexity.cpp#L2007" target="_blank" rel="noopener">tools/perplexity/perplexity.cpp — main() (L2007)</a></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Performance Hook</div>
      <div class="perf-hook">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          Every performance optimization PR in a serious inference project should include both speed numbers <em>and</em> quality validation. "Faster" alone is not enough &mdash; you need to show that logits or perplexity have not regressed. Without this, a speed win might ship a broken model.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Check Yourself</div>
      <GatePanel
        client:load
        lessonId="L38"
        gateStrength="hard"
        questions={[
          {
            id: 'L38-q1',
            type: 'single_choice',
            prompt: 'An optimization makes inference 40% faster but the logits diverge significantly from the baseline. Is this a successful optimization?',
            tag: 'reasoning',
            choices: [
              { id: 'a', text: 'Yes, because speed is the goal of optimization', isCorrect: false },
              { id: 'b', text: 'No, because different logits mean the model is producing different predictions — the speedup is not a safe drop-in replacement', isCorrect: true },
              { id: 'c', text: 'It depends only on whether the generated text looks reasonable to a human', isCorrect: false },
            ],
            explanation: 'A valid speedup must preserve model outputs. If logits diverge significantly, the model is effectively a different model that happens to be faster. It cannot be used as a drop-in replacement for the original without evaluating the quality impact.',
          },
          {
            id: 'L38-q2',
            type: 'single_choice',
            prompt: 'You optimized a kernel and decode speed improved by 25%. Perplexity on wikitext-2 went from 7.2 to 7.3. Your colleague\'s optimization improved speed by 35% but perplexity went from 7.2 to 9.1. Which optimization(s) should ship?',
            tag: 'reasoning',
            choices: [
              { id: 'a', text: 'Both — any speed improvement is worth shipping', isCorrect: false },
              { id: 'b', text: 'Yours only — the 0.1 PPL increase is within tolerance, but a jump from 7.2 to 9.1 indicates a quality regression', isCorrect: true },
              { id: 'c', text: 'Neither — perplexity changed in both cases', isCorrect: false },
            ],
            explanation: 'A 0.1 increase on a base of 7.2 (~1.4%) is small and may be acceptable depending on the application. A jump from 7.2 to 9.1 (~26% degradation) is clearly a quality regression that needs investigation. The exact tolerance depends on context — but the key principle is that you must check, and large changes are always suspicious. The first optimization warrants closer evaluation; the second almost certainly has a bug.',
          },
        ]}
      />
    </div>

  </LessonPage>
</BaseLayout>
